Sunday, January 1, 1967

Another unproductive day today. David came in this morning and told us of some turmoil at their house last night. A disagreeable situation.
Today I watched most of the American Football League Championship game between Kansas City and Buffalo; and then the National Football League Championship Game between Green Bay Packers and Dallas Cowboys. Both of them good games but I had other worries.
Tonight heard 4 sopranos on The Bell Telephone Hour.

Monday, January 2, 1967

Nothing but TV today: Rose Parade; Sugar Bowl game; Rose Bowl game; Orange Bowl game. Took all day and evening.

Tuesday, January 3, 1967

At the office this morning. A very busy day. Got considerable done.

Carded the recent items in Ecology. Made pink sheets for two items in latest Copeia by Pouch and Savage.

Took down the electric heater for repairs. Got a hair cut. Made purchases in stationary store, bakery and at Thearles (Gilbert & Sulivan "Patience")

Went to Auto Club and bought 1967 licenses.

Shaw came in the afternoon and we went over his suggestions for the correction of the additions to Chapter 3; there weren't very many.

Gas Co man came in and fixed a leak in one of my basement heaters.

At about 2PM Grant Barnes of U.C. Press called and we made a date to discuss progress next Thursday AM at 11. Hope this will save writing a long letter.

Wednesday, January 4, 1967

At the office this morning

Went to banks and drew 1966 interest at S.D. Trust and savings and First National. Deposited at Bank of America and straightened out accounts to date. Paid first installment on 1966 income tax due Jan 15, 1967.

Got some work done on accounts this afternoon. Tonight went to the Lutes cocktail party at the Forward home. A big crowd; very noisy. Got home at 8.

Also called on Mary Ann to see her new home.

Thursday, January 5, 1967

At the office this morning. Got there late as the union didn't arrive until 730.

Got some carding done; cleaned up everything unfinished.

Grant Barnes of the UC Press came in about 11 as expected and we discussed many aspects of progress (or lack of it) with the second edition. I made it clear that age was proving a sever handicap and the press was in for disappointment because the manuscript was due to slow in the becoming available. We discussed many aspects of the job. He is to write me concerning the matters discussed.

We went up to the Zoo for lunch with Shaw including Barnes' boy. We continued the discussion of the pending job; Shaw took part in the discussion. Then we went to the reptile house and looked at specimens. By that time I was pretty tired and went home. Got my desk cleaned up in the late afternoon.

Several times we talked over paper-back condensation of Rattlesnakes. I am not fond of the idea; any way it would come along much too late for me to participate.

Tanner's description of lannomi arrived today.

Friday, January 6, 1967

At the office this morning.

Wrote letters. Went to bank.

Made trial changes in 3 copies of Chapter 3 a/c of Shaw's suggestions.

Worked on Hoge footnote and gave it to Miss Schnebeyer to copy.

Went over Chatpers 1 and 2 and made some of the changes required by lannomi.

Year end accounts this afternoon and evening.

Saturday, January 7, 1967

Worked on the changes in Chapter 1 and 2 required by changes in the status of C. vegrandis, C. lannomi, and the Hoge series. Made some progress, but not much. Listened to opera, Fledermaus at noon. Worked on Xmas cards in the afternoon, recording those that have come in.

Tonight went to the "Odd Couple" a highly amusing play. Although my hearing is such that I missed a lot of the gags.

Sunday, January 8, 1967

Watched the Eagles - Colt game this morning.

Fixed my washstand soap dish; a very poor job.

Other miscellaneous work, but not a profitable day.

Monday, January 9, 1967

At the office this morning.
Dictated some letters.
Went over the changes required in Chapters 1 and 2 by lannomi, veqrandis, gloydi, and Hoge's list. Got this in better shape than before.

Meeting of the Directors of the Natural History Society from 4 to 530.

Went to the Milton Heller's cocktail party and supper at the Yacht Club tonight. Home at 930. A large party, with plenty to eat.

Tuesday, January 10, 1967

Took GG's car down to Carlson - Simpson's in the morning and called for it in the afternoon. Left mine there for a general check-up.

At the office this morning and got some general work accomplished. Went to Library for a conference with Miss Breed on La Jolla; also to Post Office to mail a package to Jeffrey. Did some shopping.

Had a conference with Walt Zutlaw and Bennet on Torrey Pines Park; also on proposed investigation by Stanford Research by infrared loose connectors. Also on reverse osmosis progress.

Got the Hoge footnote from Miss Schneberger today.

At 630 went to Love's reception for Dumke of State Colleges at Kona Kai; then to San Diego Symphony Lowie Lane, great conductor, Maralyn Horne soloist. An enjoyable concert although had a cold.

Wednesday, January 11, 1967

At the office this morning.

Wrote letters. Determined how to insert the Hoge footnote; a difficult problem.

Called for my 1962 Chev this afternoon.

Went up to have a visit with Allan.

At the office this morning.

Inserted all references to the Hoge footnote; an extremely complicated process.

Also did some carding.

Friday, January 13, 1967

At the office this morning.

Meeting of Library Commission from 930 to 1130. Mostly discussion of La Jolla.

Kohler returned corrected maps today.

Saturday, January 14, 1967

This morning I worked on the incorporation of lannomi in the proofs of Chapters 1 and 2. Made progress in this rather complicated affair but didn't finish it.

Went over to Coronado at noon to call on the Col. Kelly's. They took me to lunch at the Coronado Hotel. We got home at 3.

Went to Los Angeles Philharmonic tonight. Got there late and had to miss the first number.

Bernard Haitink was guest conductor and he was very good. Especially enjoyed Schubert's 9th Symphony.

Sunday, January 15, 1967

This morning I finished the changes required in the U.C. proofs of Chapters 1 and 2 required by C. lannomi. Also worked on vegrandes but didn't finish.

Watched the Super Bowl football game between Green Bay Packers and Kansas City Chiefs. First half good; second half one
sided in favor of Green Bay.

Worked on the entries in the latest edition of the Zoological Record that arrived yesterday. Section reptilia.

At the office this morning.

Meeting of the Executive Committee, 930 until noon; meeting of Board of Directors until 230.

Tuesday, January 17, 1967

At the office this morning.

Had a pretty good morning; got considerable accomplished.

Inserted all the necessary vegrandis entries in Chapters 1 and 2 (except tables and figure legends). Also misc. changes.

Did some carding.

Miss Breed came over to discuss wording of the La Jolla motion made at last meeting to be transmitted to City Manager and Council.

AMNH 12 pickled rattlers arrived and were unpacked this afternoon.

Wednesday, January 18, 1967

At the office this morning. Didn't do as well as expected.

Wrote letters. Checked prior work on tables and maps. Did considerable carding.

Thursday, January 19, 1967

At the office this morning.

Had a brief conference with Sinnott.

Made up a manuscript page for the map legends in Chapter 2, so that all changes in figs 2:1 to 2:10 inclusive can
be easily set.

Also did considerable carding, cleaning up all unfinished items.

Got a ticket while homeward bound. Cops caught me on 3 items at 11th and E.
1) turned into other than left lane
2) turned too late when yellow light almost finished
3) didn't stop quickly enough when he gave me his headlights and siren. As usual I didn't know he meant me right away.

The ticket mentions only no. 3.

Tonight went to the D'Oyly Carte Opera Co in Patience. Took Clara. A bad fog in taking her home.

At the office this morning.

Business at the bank and library.

Worked a little on identification series of photos.

Did carding this afternoon.

Saturday, January 21, 1967

Worked on Snelling's suggested changes in the ranges of horridus & atricaudatus in North Carolina and Virginia and dictated a letter to Snelling.

Did some work on the identification series of photos.

Took Janet and Laurie to the Chuck Wagon for supper tonight, and then home to watch TV (which was lousy). They stayed all night.

Monday, January 23, 1967

At the office this morning.
Wrote letters.
Howard Chernoff called; he is home for good. Talked over future plans, particularly re San Pasqual.

Worked on the identification series of pictures and made progress, particularly of the serial number system. Got tired out by 11AM.

Tuesday, January 24, 1967

At the office this morning.
Spent a lot of time rearranging the photos of the identification series.
Also some shopping.
In the afternoon continued numbering of all the photos, took 3 hours.
Went to San Diego Symphony Concert tonight. Got caught in a strong rainstorm on the way home.

Wednesday, January 25, 1967

At the office this morning. Worked hard on a list of the identification series of photos to be submitted to the UC Press. Made good progress.

Went to the Zoo Trustees meeting tonight. A fairly peaceful meeting. Got home at 830.

Thursday, January 26, 1967

At the office this morning.

Had several phone conferences with Chernoff.

Picked out the identification series of plates and put in the crop lines. Finished most of them but not all.

At noon went to a Combo II lunch at the Cuyamaca Club. Lasted until 2PM. This was the beneficiary committee in person.

Friday, January 27, 1967

At the office this morning.

Cropped most of the foreign prints in the identification series.

Went over to the Library and the post office.

Sloan came over this afternoon with the AMNH specimens. These were recently received and he has counted them. Several of the specimens don't agree with the classification on the invoice. They will have to be checked carefully.

Showed Sloan the Tashjian colored slides. He said the sand backgrounds could be cleaned up.

Called Kobber this morning. Got some opaque white or show-card white that can be used for cleaning up backgrounds.

Tonight went to the Ballet Folklorico of Mexico at Community Theater. A very enjoyable performance.

Saturday, January 28, 1967

Wrote a letter to Larry and Terry on their marriage.

Worked almost all day preparing a set of photographs of the identification series to send to the UC Press. Made good progress on cropping etc. A very involved and complicated project.

Arranged the identification series in proper order. Picked up other odds and ends. Worked some on the AMNH specimens.

Monday, January 30, 1967

At the office this morning.

Called Sloan at Nat Hist Mus about some photos; need some negatives for the identification series.

Had a brief conference with Joe Sinnott.

Did some carding.

Checked the U.C. people for change with the figure numbers of the identification series. This was a long, involved job. Finished the first check. Made many changes.

A Mrs. C Adameon 214-7354 called me up this afternoon to complain about the treatment she received from the Library and other city employees and institutions. They have hypnotized her etc. I find that she is clearly insane, but it was a very trying and lengthy conversation. Most of this happened more than 8 years ago.

A young herpetological enthusiast Steve Campbell came in at 330 and talked over his problems until 505. He wants to be a herpetologist but has no skills, education, or money. A tough problem.

The Chernoffs came to dinner tonight. Talked over many things.

Wednesday, February 1, 1967

Met in Judge Fred Kunzele's office from 810 AM to 950 with Howard Chernoff to describe Zoo problems.

At the office 10 to 1130. Did some carding and letter writing. Not much else.

Went to Cuyamaca Club 1145 to 145. Had lunch with the Arthur Johnson. The guest of honor was Francis Robinson of the Met, N.Y. Most of the comments were about Opera.

Thursday, February 2, 1967

This morning mailed the proofs of chapters 1 and 2 to U.C.

Arranged to buy some photos for the identification series from Barnell. Quite a while required to arrange these.

Also took care of business at the bank.

Had a brief conference with Sinnott.

Friday, February 3, 1967

Got up early this morning (before 3) and arranged annual inventory papers, and income tax data for 1966.

At the office this morning.

Went to safety deposit box and got papers necessary to figure 1966 earnings and income tax.

Reread chapter 3.

Conference with Walter re loose connector detectors; also smog.

Dictated letters.

Saturday, February 4, 1967

Worked on monthly accounts and brought them down to date.

Worked on the annual 1966 inventory and made good progress, although I did not complete the calculation.

Went to the Charity Ball at Coronado Hotel tonight. Started with the Wohlford Cocktail Party, then dinner, then a ball in the Crown Room with the most awful, noisy music ever heard. Oscar and Lenore drove me over and back. In our table and box had the Lacy's, and Violet and Fanny Sherman.

Sunday, February 5, 1967

Got a little work done on tabulation of 1966 Income Tax Data and also 1966 inventory. Didn't do as much because Dave and Grave came down for a visit in the morning.

Took them to the Chuck Wagon for dinner tonight.

Monday, February 6, 1967

At the office this morning.

Had a call from Chernoff about tonight's Zoo meeting.

Made Thermofax copies of Kaplan's report for Chernoff and myself.

Went to the bank.

Settled with PMK about our S.D. Symphony donation.

Wrote letters, including one to Parrish.

Did a little work on the 1966 data take off for annual statement and income tax report. Found I was pretty tired by 11 AM.

Findlay Russell called from LA this afternoon. Wants a copy of Fred Shannnon's letter about the bite of the Sonoran Coral Snake.

Went to the Zoo 50th Anniversary Party tonight from 630 to 9. A free loader, glad haven affair. Grace fell down where a car was blocking the exit walkway.

Tuesday, February 7, 1967

At the office this morning.

Wrote letters.

Talked to Chernoff about last night's meeting at the Zoo.

Worked on take-off date for Federal Taxes and also annual inventory. Made progress, but it goes slowly.

Went to the library and post office. Mailed racer scale counts to Larry Wilson at Baton Rouge; and chapter 3 manuscript to U.C. Press.

Time for annual inventory and income tax greatly slows up work in Rattlesnake.

Concert of San Diego Symphony tonight. Igler Solomon, guest conductor, Gary Graffman piano soloist.

Friday, February 10, 1967

At the office for a brief time this morning, but spent most of the morning at the meeting of the Library Commission. Willhelm the new asst. City Manager was present. Put in time discussing La Jolla, as usual.

Worked in the afternoon and got miscellaneous work done.

Saturday, February 18, 1967

Today I worked on the Mexican rattlers borrowed from Boget of the AMNH. Made some progress, but not too good. The scutes, of which there were several, were easy to diagnose but the several related to the triseuatas, pricei and/or intermedius were more difficult, especially as they are small and not in the best condition. My poor eyes are a severe handicap. I shall have to put in more time on them.

Went to Scholia tonight at the Zoo. Walter Hepner talked on "America's Future: Optimistic or Pessimistic? Have We Lost Our Dream?"

Rather long; didn't get home until after 10. My discussion was poor.

Sunday, February 19, 1967

Today I did some work on the two AMNH specimens from Durango identified as pricei. They are certainly not intermedius or triseriatus they are much like the pricei I had previously seen from Aguas Calientes. This will require further study.

We had a dinner party at home tonight; 10 people: Geo Phillyes and his new wife Miss Daly; the Lacy's; Eileen and Everett Jackson; Vecar Cotton (who arrived late), Winnie Wright, and Mrs Innes. I showed Phillyes my association copies of books in which he was considerably interested.

Tuesday, February 28, 1967

Attended a meeting of the Economic Research Bureau at the Cuyamaca Club from 730 AM to 915.

This morning I had a talk with Sinnott about the future of my job with the company. Told him I no longer wished a salary for my consulting work which had become virtually useless to the company. He said the decision was up to me; he hadn't wished to make a decision on the similar proposal I had made a couple of months ago. I said I would like to retain the office and some of the other facilities; any one would be free to consult me on company business at any time, but there would be no charge. This was OK with Joe. Also talked to Cox and Phil My salary will cease today; the first time I have been off the payroll since January 1911.

Went to Post Office, Library and Bank. Not much else done. I am glad the matter is settled. Joe and I had been badly treated by the company. I said this was long ago; no one now with the company had had anything to do with that ancient history.

Tuesday, May 16, 1967

Spent a lot of time today on a complete phyiscal examination by Dr. George Fishburn. Examination lasted from 1015 AM until 1230.

The electrocadiograph showed a considerable deterioration since the last examination last March. George explained the difference but it was too technical for me to understand. What I did learn was that there is no reason why I shouldn't take nitroglycerin to relieve the pain by angina whenever I needed it; the repeated use is not deleterious. This is a great relief to me as I had not taken as much or as often as I seemed to need it.

He decided to put me on a course of Coumadin. First said I shouldn't go to the hospital for 3 days to a week so the effect could be noted but I kicked at this and it was finally agreed that a technician would come to the house and make the required tests here. This will be much more convenient for me. Will begin tomorrow AM.

Had an extra blood test this AM and also X-ray, to determine what causes my hip trouble.

Took a urine sample up to Fishburn's office this afternoon; also had my glasses fixed. I think the tests so far have been very thorough, and they have been a relief to me.

Wednesday, May 24, 1967

This morning Winters came at 8 and made the usual blood test. Fishburn called at the office in mid morning. He said I was to take a whole tablet of coumadin today.

I told him I was getting fed up on the blood tests; they were a nuisance and spoiled my day. He said they would probably end this week and then I would have them at weekly or monthly intervals. Told him I was annoyed by considerable skipping. He said he was going to see me next week for a re-examination and would then decide on a future course of treatment.

At the office this morning. Read many reports.

Called Chernoff and had 2 long talks on San Pasqual. The proposed meeting with Fred Kirnzel was called off for this afternoon. He promised to write a letter about legality.

Talked with Miss Breed about a trip to La Jolla to look at Library sites. Maybe next Monday.

Worked some on Chapter 4 but got nothing done as there were too many interruptions.

Attended a long meeting of the Zoo Board of Trustees tonight. Didn't get home until 10. Raised the gate to 125. I voted no. Long discussion of San Pasqual, mostly non-pertinent.

Monday, May 29, 1967

At 830 this morning Miss Breed picked me up and we drove out to La Jolla. First went to residence of Mrs. Vernon Gaston where we met Tom Scripps and Mrs. Widman. Drove around La Jolla in Scripps' station wagon and looked at about 10 possible sites. Then went back to Gaston's and sat in the car and discussed the good and bad points of the sites. Will have another special meeting to see what can be worked out. June 6th was suggested.

Saw Dr. Fishburn this afternoon at 2 and was given another physical examination. He was quite thorough in our discussions of my recent difficulties, especially the episode after Combo.

He phoned later and told me the urine was now OK; also the heart showed what he had expected to get out of Coumadin. Told me to discontinue Persantin, which I hadn't been taking recently anyway. He now prescribed Isordil + Phenobarbital which I am beginning at once.

I am to see him again in about 2 weeks.

Wednesday, May 31, 1967

At the office this morning.

First cleared up reading a lot of reports

Then tackled hybrids once more and finally finished it. All that remains now is to make two manuscript copies - one for the Press, one for reserve. Can't do this until prior parts are finished so that inserts can be given appropriate serial letters.

Shaw came around this afternoon with 33m pictures lately taken by Ron Garrison: S.miliarius from Carolina; C enyo furvus from B.C.; and C.v.oreganus from SW Oregon. All were good except the latter.

Worked on the early parts of chapter 4 and made some progress. But it is clear that too much time is lost getting oriented when it is dropped for a few days. I will have to work on it continually to a finish or it will never get done.

Friday, June 2, 1967

Went to dinner tonight at the new Atlantis cafe with Lacey's; also Clara and Dorsca. Had a fine dinner; then to the South Seas show at Sea World (the above belongs with previous page).

At the office this morning. Tackled the saccular lung and made considerable progress. It was quite satisfactory.

Talked to Larry late this evening.

Ray Cowles called from the Zoo this afternoon. We had a brief chat but I got switched to Chuck Shaw before we finished.

After supper I went over to the Zoo and had another talk with Ray about his present activities. We talked for about an hour. He has another book on the South African problems submitted to the University of Oklahoma Press but some of the anthropologists are highly critical, so maybe it won't be published.

Then went to Philadelphia Symphony concert which I greatly enjoyed: Tocata and Fugue by Bach; Don Quixote by R Strauss and Sibelius Symphony no 2. The last was by far the finest item.

Tonight went to Winnie Wright's party at Kona Kai. Drosea with us. Home at 1015.

Friday, August 11, 1967

At the office this morning from 1145 to noon. Picked up mail.
Meeting of the Smog Citizens Advisory Committee from 930 to 1145. Every member present. First committee meeting for more than a year. From the north came John A Maga, Chief, Bureau of Air Sanitation State Department of Public Health and Eric P. Grant, Executive Officer, Motor Vehicle Control Board. They made full reports on new laws and other developments. Also we had the reports of Askew's office on recent San Diego County statistics, including some high last-winter readings. It was recommended that the committee become more active in the future.
Tonight had a buffet supper at home for Larry and Terry. About 45 or 50 present. A lively party; everything went off quite well.

Thursday, September 28, 1967

Slept badly last night.

Was tired this morning; did nothing at the office except read.

Tonight went to a dinner meeting of the San Diego Academy of Medicine at the Town and Country Hotel in Mission Valley. This was to talk on Annual Venoms by Findlay Russell. It was a large well attended meeting. Dr. Minton Fetter took me out. I was supposed to introduce Russell which I did but it was a poor job as the light was poor and I couldn't see what I had written.

The talk, illustrated by slides and also with a few live rattlesnakes in boxes, was excellent and was received enthusiastically. He recounted many interesting experiences not only on snake bite but also on arthropod bites and stings. Was very much worth while.

Friday, November 10, 1967

I was very tired at the end of the meeting.

Sunday, November 12, 1967

A busy social day.
Went to Col. Wm Kelly's for lunch in Coronado. His sister and mother-in-law also there. Got home at 330.

Tonight went to Starkey's dinner at the Cuyamaca Club. Black tie; big crowd. Then went to concert of Los Angeles Philharmonic Orchestra. Very enjoyable. First Von Weber's Overture to Everyanthe; then Shauss Tone Poem: Don Juan which was very fine. This was to be followed by Buckners' 7th Symphony which they didn't give, as many members of the Orchestra were ill; instead they gave Dvorak's 8th Symphony followed by an encore Wagner's prelude to Lohengrim. Altogether it was a fine concert. Mehta was in good form. Tired out this morning.

Tuesday, December 5, 1967

Another very discouraging day as far as the driver's test was concerned.
Went out 94 and missed the proper turnoff. Went back to town and came out University and finally found it. But I failed in the eye test and also the questions and answers. The list I was given was different from any I had before.
Got home for lunch at 230 and was completely exhausted. Could hardly eat.

Page Edit History:
  • jrabbers 07/13/2011 01:21 PM
  • JDonner 02/24/2011 07:16 PM
  • psully 11/23/2010 01:16 PM

Wednesday, December 6, 1967

Had a tough night tonight as I expected to go out to La Mesa for my driver's test. Was worried about the test and also finding the La Mesa office of the Motor Vehicle department. However drove out on 94 and found the office without much trouble. Registered for the test and got a tester without too much trouble. The test went fairly OK but of course I made all the usual mistakes. I was given a final score of 27 points off or 73 out of 100.

When I went in to the window in the office I didn't take in my score sheet which was probably an error; it was left lying in the front sheet. The letter had said I am going to recommended you for a 3-year extension which of course was highly satisfactory to me. However the man at the window left for a few minutes (probably to consult the tally sheet) and then reported the had agreed to give me a one year extension. This was very disappointing after what the examiner had told me. I shall write them and ask why.

Went over to a library lunch at Kona Kai with Bill Lacy this noon. Lucky I went although I was pretty well pooped.

Took a lot of magazines to the library.
Wrote letters to Copley and Pourade.
Declined the Old Timers invitations to Maxine Hoopes.
Worked on charitable cards.
Did some work on Xmas cards.
In the afternoon made out checks for all charitable organizations.

Sunday, December 24, 1967

Melville Klauber, Sylvia, and his six kids came down to call this morning.
At 11AM Dr. Norton B Stern called and interviewed me on Abraham Klauber. He is gathering information on Pacific Coast pioneer Jewish people. Gave him what I could and promised him a copy of my unfinished biography of my father.
His full name Dr. Norton B. Stern optometrist 830 Lincoln Blvd, Venice, Calif. EX 9-3585, zip 90291

GG went to Alice Stewarts in the late afternoon.
Philip already has a copy of the AK biography.
Worked this afternoon rearranging the AK biography.

Chuck Wagon

Midway Chuck Wagon
Midway Drive at Rosecrans
San Diego 6, Calif.

Delicious choice of prime ribs -- all you can eat for $2.29 is the slogan of the Midway Chuck Wagon. Customers are invited to dine "Chuck Wagon Style" in a quaint Western atmosphere. Enjoy your favorite cocktails in the unique Gaslight Bar or the Longbranch Saloon where top names in the entertainment world will entertain you. The policy of giving the people what they want in quality... price... and service... has made the Midway Chuck Wagon the outstanding eating and entertainment attraction of the West.
